╭─ Assistant [MainThread@639888] ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ The bug is caused by the SLP vectorizer incorrectly transforming a horizontal reduction    │
│ that involves `select` instructions. The `select` instruction has control-flow semantics   │
│ that can prevent `poison` from propagating from an unselected operand. The vectorized      │
│ version, however, unconditionally evaluates all operands in a vector, which can lead to    │
│ `poison` propagating where it would not in the original scalar code. This violates the     │
│ `poison` semantics and leads to a miscompilation.                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The reproducer demonstrates this:                                                          │
│ ```llvm                                                                                    │
│ define i1 @test(i32 %x, i32 %a, i32 %b, i32 %c, i32 %d) {                                  │
│   %cmp = icmp sgt i32 %x, 1                                                                │
│   %cmp2 = icmp sgt i32 %b, 1                                                               │
│   %cmp3 = icmp sgt i32 %c, 1                                                               │
│   %cmp4 = icmp sgt i32 %d, 1                                                               │
│   %sel2 = select i1 %cmp4, i1 true, i1 %cmp2                                               │
│   %sel3 = select i1 %sel2, i1 true, i1 %cmp3                                               │
│   %sel4 = select i1 %cmp, i1 true, i1 %cmp4                                                │
│   %ret = or i1 %sel3, %sel4                                                                │
│   ret i1 %ret                                                                              │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│ The chain of `select` and `or` instructions is identified as a horizontal `or`-reduction.  │
│ For example, if `%sel2` is true, the value of `%cmp3` (which could be `poison`) is ignored │
│ in the scalar code. The vectorized code, however, computes all comparisons (`%cmp`,        │
│ `%cmp2`, `%cmp3`, `%cmp4`) in a vector, and then performs a vector reduction. If `%cmp3`   │
│ is `poison`, the final result of the reduction will be `poison`, which is incorrect.       │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to disable this horizontal reduction vectorization when the reduction tree      │
│ contains `select` instructions. This is a conservative but safe approach to prevent this   │
│ miscompilation. The check is added at the beginning of                                     │
